      "contents": "<p xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml\" id=\"MPParagraphElement:521D99A4-BA67-42D7-B9E9-1DA89A355BDF\" class=\"MPElement\" data-object-type=\"MPParagraphElement\">A 19-bp insertion/deletion polymorphism localized 4.5kb from <i>DβH</i> 5’ flank transcriptional starting site on chromosome 9q34 is named <i>DβH</i> 5’-Ins/Del polymorphism. It is a functional locus, which has been reported to influence DβH activity. The pDβH activity in individuals with <i>DβH</i> 5’-Del/Del is only half of those in individuals with <i>DβH</i> 5’-Ins/Ins. Previous studies have indicated that this polymorphism is associated with cognitive abnormality in older women, average reaction response time in Chinese females, attention bias for negative faces in the young subjects, and post-error slowing in the young Caucasian healthy adults that are correlated with suicidal behavior. <i>DβH</i> haplotype (consisting of <i>DβH</i> 5'-del allele and 11 allele of GT<sub>n</sub> repeats) is linked to suicide attempts in schizophrenia. Interestingly, <i>DβH</i> 5’-Ins/Del polymorphism is implicated in attention in patients with chronic schizophrenia. Taken together, these results suggest that this polymorphism might be involved in cognitive regulation and the development of suicide attempts in chronic schizophrenia. However, no studies have examined <i>DβH</i> 5’-Ins/Del polymorphism in relation to cognitive function and the development of suicide attempts in chronic schizophrenia. Thus, the objectives of this study are to examine whether <i>DβH</i> 5’-Ins/Del polymorphism influences cognitive regulation, and further contributes to the development of suicide attempts in chronic schizophrenia.</p>",
